{"id":14881029,"mediaExerciseId":"f11cd4be-813e-4ef8-a465-52c951cea7c6","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"7","chapterTitle":"Interest Rates and Bond Valuation","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"7.4","sectionTitle":"Some Different Types of Bonds","pageNumber":218,"solutions":[{"id":5963424,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This task asks **why the companies are still interested in issuing income bonds. Then, we should determine how adding additional features to the bond will affect the securities.**\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":100,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/af1e876701da5acc27bc756b1a4c1f74/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":51,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/af1e876701da5acc27bc756b1a4c1f74/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Income bonds and convertible bonds are closely related. The difference is that the payment of the first one depends on the company's income. The company will pay the bond just if the income is high enough. **If the company does not contribute enough profit will not pay the bond.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/d61920b1da95279ba2606d750a0fcf8b/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/d61920b1da95279ba2606d750a0fcf8b/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"*This bond is still attractive for risky companies*. The company is unsure if it will contribute profit to pay the debt. That is why they will issue an income bond to lower the loss if it happens. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/b5102beb729f2f13244b45209ec707d6/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/b5102beb729f2f13244b45209ec707d6/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"This kind of debt is not usual because if the investor invests in the bonds, he wants to be sure that he will be investing in a profitable investment. Otherwise, the investor can invest in the stocks and have additional voting right. **That is the reason why the demand for the income bond is decreasing.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/44e9ff225c3619c10c55c41d60896b53/lateximg_large.png","width":1039},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/44e9ff225c3619c10c55c41d60896b53/lateximg.png","width":521}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"**b)**\n\nIf we set the **put** features on the bond, the bond's holder has a right to force the issuer to buy at the stated price back the security. **Because of this feature, the coupon will be lower.**\n\n**A convertible** bond means the bond can be exchanged for stock whenever the option's holder wants it before its maturity. **Because of the flexibility, the coupon will be less worth it.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":256,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/49bb620f9f2fc63445ff66a5267a5b17/lateximg_large.png","width":1000},"regular":{"height":128,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c103a225cc519357fadb83d0f76619f2/49bb620f9f2fc63445ff66a5267a5b17/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"a9b8eaf7-c4af-4b67-a7ca-0e7061ad163d","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881030,"exerciseName":"1","page":219,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"2c3ebd31-ed66-4c65-8ecf-9df02ad167ac","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-7-exercises-1-2c3ebd31-ed66-4c65-8ecf-9df02ad167ac"},{"id":14881031,"exerciseName":"2","page":219,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"47952eea-978c-44bf-8083-6f9ffcda2443","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-7-exercises-2-47952eea-978c-44bf-8083-6f9ffcda2443"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881028,"exerciseName":"3","page":212,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"f2060cad-0b33-4b9a-8791-9c72af22734e","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-7-exercises-3-f2060cad-0b33-4b9a-8791-9c72af22734e"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-